Theory :

•  Definition of fork(): 
	fork() is a system call used in Unix/Linux to create a new process. 
•  Parent and Child Process: 
	The original process is called the parent process. 
	The newly created process is called the child process. 
•  Process Creation: 
	After calling fork(), a duplicate process is created. 
	Both parent and child execute independently. 
•  Return Values of fork(): 
	> 0 → Returned to parent, gives child’s PID 
	0 → Returned to child process 
	-1 → Error (process creation failed) 
•  Execution Behavior: 
	Both processes start execution from the next line after fork(). 
	They run concurrently (order of execution is not fixed). 
•  Process Identification: 
	getpid() → returns current process ID 
	getppid() → returns parent process ID 
•  Memory Handling: 
	Child process gets a copy of parent’s memory (separate address space). 
•  Importance of fork(): 
	Used for multitasking and parallel execution 
	Fundamental for process management in OS
------------------------------------------------------------------------------


#include <stdio.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/types.h>

int main() {
    pid_t pid;

    pid = fork();   // create child process

    if (pid < 0) {
        perror("Fork failed");
        return 1;
    }
    else if (pid == 0) {
        printf("This is the child process.\n");
        printf("Child PID: %d\n", getpid());
        printf("Parent PPID: %d\n", getppid());
    }
    else {
        printf("This is the parent process.\n");
        printf("Parent PID: %d\n", getpid());
        printf("Child PID: %d\n", pid);
    }

    return 0;
}


